Safety. Although regulatory authorities recommend avoiding the use in pregnancy and lactation (
 EMA, 2011b), ginger use during pregnancy was reported as safe in Canadian, Australian and Norwegian women (
 Portnoi et al., 2003; 
 Willetts et al., 2003; 
 Westfall, 2004; 
 Heitmann et al., 2013). Clinical studies found ginger as effective and safe to prevent pregnancy-associated nausea and vomiting (
 Borrelli et al., 2005; 
 Ding et al., 2013). In human liver microsomes, the hydroethanolic extract inhibited CYP2C19 and CYP2D6 (
 Kim et al., 2012; 
 Gorman et al., 2013).
